'''Severe Tropical Cyclone Susan''' was one of [[List of the most intense tropical cyclones#South Pacific Ocean|the most intense tropical cyclones]] on record within the [[Tropical cyclone basins#South Pacific Ocean|South Pacific basin]], which was first noted on December 20, 1997, as a weak [[tropical disturbance]] located to the north of [[American Samoa]]. Over the next 12 days, the disturbance remained weak while it gradually moved towards the southwest before it started to rapidly develop on January 2, 1998 while it was located near the [[Fiji]]an dependency of [[Rotuma]]. The disturbance was declared a [[tropical cyclone]] later that day, but was not [[Tropical cyclone naming|named]] Susan until the next day, after it had intensified into a category 2 tropical cyclone on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#Australia and Fiji|Australian Scale]]. Over the next few days, Susan moved towards the southwest and continued to intensify before it reached its peak intensities as a [[Tropical cyclone scales|category five tropical cyclone]] during January 5 while it was located about {{Convert|400|km|mi|disp=5|abbr=on}} to the northwest of [[Vanuatu]]'s [[capital city]] [[Port Vila]].

At this stage as the cyclone was moving towards the southwest it posed a severe threat to Vanuatu however, during that day Susan recurved towards the southeast and subsequently spared Vanuatu a direct hit. After sparing Vanuatu a direct hit, Susan started to accelerate towards the southeast and while starting to weaken significantly passed close enough to Fiji during January 7 and 8 to cause [[Beaufort scale|gale force winds]] in Fiji's southern and western islands. While continuing to move towards the southeast, Susan started to interact with [[Cyclone Ron|Severe Tropical Cyclone Ron]] during January 8 before it absorbed Ron by 0600&nbsp;UTC the next day and starting to transition into an extratropical cyclone. The extratropical remnants of the combined systems were then monitored for another day until they were last noted on January 10, bringing an unseasonable cold snap to [[New Zealand]]. Despite sparing Vanuatu and Fiji direct hits, heavy rain and gale force winds associated with Susan were reported to have caused minor damage to several Vanuatuan and Fijian islands. These islands included [[Viti Levu]] where a possible [[tornado]] destroyed the roof of a shopping centre and the Vanuatuan island of [[Aoba Island|Ambrym]], where a woman died after being hit by a falling coconut tree, while gathering supplies to secure her house with.

==Meteorological History==
{{Storm path|Susan 1997 track.png}}
On December 20, 1997, the [[Fiji Meteorological Service]]'s [[Regional Specialized Meteorological Center]] in [[Nadi, Fiji]] (RSMC Nadi), started to monitor a weak [[tropical disturbance]] that was located about {{convert|915|km|mi|disp=5|abbr=on}}, to the northwest of [[Pago-Pago]] in [[American Samoa]].<ref name="Jan 98">{{cite web|title=Monthly Global Tropical Cyclone Summary January 1998|author=Padgett, Gary|date=March 18, 2008|url=http://australiasevereweather.com/cyclones/1998/summ9801.htm|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name="11P BT">{{cite web|publisher=United States Navy, United States Air Force|author2=Naval Pacific Meteorology and Oceanography Center|author1=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|archivedate=January 1, 2012|url=http://www.usno.navy.mil/NOOC/nmfc-ph/RSS/jtwc/best_tracks/1998/1998s-bsh/bsh111998.txt|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/64NPmi6lo|deadurl=no|accessdate=February 28, 2014|title=Tropical Cyclone 11P (Susan) best track analysis}}</ref> Over the next two weeks the system gradually moved towards the west-southwest, without developing into a tropical cyclone.<ref name="Jan 98"/> During January 2, a mid-level ridge of high pressure developed between Fiji and Vanuatu, which provided an area of low vertical wind shear.<ref name="IHS">{{cite book|title=Forests, water, and people in the humid tropics: past, present, and future hydrological research for integrated land and water management|series=International Hydrological Series|editors=Bonell, Michael; Bruijnzeel, Leendert Adrian|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2005|isbn=0-521-82953-4|author1=Bonell, Michael|author2=Callaghan, Jeff|author3=Connor, G|pages=196<U+2013>198|url=http://books.google.com/?id=OC40vch1JjoC&pg=PA195&lpg=PA195&dq=%22Cyclone+Susan%22#v=onepage&q&f=false|chapter=Chapter 11: Synoptic and mesoscale rain producing systems in the humid tropics}}</ref> The system subsequently started to show signs of significant development, before early on January 3, the United States [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] <small>(JTWC)</small> initiated warnings on the system and designated it as Tropical Cyclone 11P.<ref>{{cite web|date=January 3, 1998|title=Tropical Cyclone 11P (Susan) Warning 1 January 3, 1998 0000z|publisher=United States Navy, United States Air Force|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 18, 2011|url=http://www.nrlmry.navy.mil/atcf_web/docs/warnings/1998/sh111998.98010300.wrn|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/64NNbjvQS|archivedate=January 1, 2012|deadurl=no|author=Joint Typhoon Warning Center}}</ref> RSMC Nadi subsequently reported later that day that the depression had intensified into a category 1 tropical cyclone, on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#Australia and Fiji|Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]], while located near the Fiji dependency of [[Rotuma]].<ref name="Susan Prem report">{{cite report|author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;<U+2014> Tropical Cyclone Centre|title=Preliminary Report on Tropical Cyclone Susan&nbsp;<U+2014> January 3 - 9, 1998|publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service|date=January 20, 1998|accessdate=December 14, 2013|url=http://www.pacificdisaster.net/pdnadmin/data/original/CRP_TC_1998_Preliminary_report.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6LryJ3hi2|archivedate=December 14, 2013}}</ref> During that day the system continued to rapidly develop with RSMC Nadi reporting early on January 4, that Susan had become a category 3 severe tropical cyclone, with 10-minute sustained windspeeds of 120&nbsp;km/h (75&nbsp;mph).<ref name="97-98 BT">{{cite web|work=Fiji Meteorological Service|title=Best Track Data for the 1997<U+2013>98 season|publisher=United States: International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|url=ftp://eclipse.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/ibtracs/original-bt-data-files/nadi/RSMC%20Nadi%209798%20BT%20Data.txt.txt|author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;<U+2014> Tropical Cyclone Centre|accessdate=May 29, 2011|date=May 22, 2009}}</ref> During January 4, Susan continued to rapidly intensify with the JTWC reporting that Susan had become equivalent to a category 1 hurricane on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]] as convection surrounding the system organized further and developed an eye feature.<ref name="11P BT"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Tropical Cyclone 11P (Susan) Warning 4, January 4, 1998 1200z|accessdate=July 18, 2011|date=January 4, 1998|url=http://www.nrlmry.navy.mil/atcf_web/docs/warnings/1998/sh111998.98010412.wrn|author=Joint Typhoon Warning Center|publisher=United States Navy, United States Air Force}}</ref>
