<ref name="1997-98 BoM">{{cite journal|publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology|title=The South Pacific and Southeast Indian Ocean Tropical Cyclone Season 1997<U+2013>98|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/amm/docs/2000/chappel.pdf|accessdate=July 23, 2013|author1=Chappel Lori-Carmen|volume=49|pages=121<U+2013>138|author2=Bate Peter W|date=June 2, 2000|journal=Australian Meteorological Magazine (Australian Meteorological and Oceanographic Journal)|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110605113928/http://www.bom.gov.au/amm/docs/2000/chappel.pdf|archivedate=June 5, 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref> 

<ref name="97-98 ATCR">{{cite report|publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service|title=RSMC Nadi Tropical Cyclone Seasonal Summary 1997-98|date=August 29, 2007|accessdate=December 14, 2013|url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_97-981190690538.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5rfDHEnbo|author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;<U+2014> Tropical Cyclone Centre|archivedate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> -->

[[File:Cyclones Ron and Susan.png|thumb|right|200px|Cyclone Susan absorbing Cyclone Ron]]
As the ridge of high pressure that was located to the south of the cyclone started to weaken, which meant that Susan started to move further towards the southwest.<ref name="DTDSJAN98">{{cite journal|year=1998|title=January 1998|journal=Darwin Tropical Diagnostic Statement|publisher=Bureau of Meteorology|location=Australian|volume=17|issue=1|author=Darwin Regional Specialised Meteorological Centre|pages=2<U+2013>3|issn=1321-4233|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/ntregion/statements/tropical/dtds-199801.pdf|accessdate=January 11, 2012}}</ref> RSMC Nadi then reported at 0000&nbsp;UTC on January 5, that the system had become a category 5 severe tropical cyclone with 10-minute sustained wind speeds of 140&nbsp;mph (220&nbsp;km/h), before reporting 6 hours later that Susan had reached its peak 10-minute sustained wind speeds of 145&nbsp;mph (225&nbsp;km/h) and a peak pressure of 900&nbsp;hPa (26.58&nbsp;inHg).{{TCWC Wellington BT}} Around this time RSMC Nadi reported that the system might of developed a double eye feature while the JTWC reported that Susan had peaked with 1-minute wind speeds of 260&nbsp;km/h (160&nbsp;mph) equivalent to a weak category five hurricane on the SSHS.<ref name="11P BT"/><ref name="DTDSJAN98"/> As the system reached its peak intensity, Susan was moving towards the southwest and as a result, it "posed a severe threat to Vanuatu," however during that afternoon, Susan recurved towards the southeast "just in time to spare Vanuatu, a direct hit.<U+201D><ref name="97-98 ATCR">{{cite report|publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service|title=RSMC Nadi Tropical Cyclone Seasonal Summary 1997-98|date=August 29, 2007|accessdate=December 14, 2013|url=http://www.met.gov.fj/documents/TC_Seasonal_Summary_97-981190690538.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5rfDHEnbo|author=RSMC Nadi&nbsp;<U+2014> Tropical Cyclone Centre|archivedate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> After turning away from Vanuatu, Susan accelerated towards the southeast while remaining near or at its peak intensities, before starting to weaken significantly during January 7.<ref name="Wellington BT"/> RSMC Nadi then reported early the next day, that Susan had weakened into a category 4 severe tropical cyclone while it was located about {{Convert|435|km|disp=5|abbr=on}}, to the southeast of Nadi, Fiji, which was close enough for the system to produce gale force winds in several southern and western [[Fijian Islands]].<ref name="1997-98 BoM">{{cite journal|publisher=Australian Bureau of Meteorology|title=The South Pacific and Southeast Indian Ocean Tropical Cyclone Season 1997<U+2013>98|url=http://www.bom.gov.au/amm/docs/2000/chappel.pdf|accessdate=July 23, 2013|author1=Chappel Lori-Carmen|volume=49|pages=121<U+2013>138|author2=Bate Peter W|date=June 2, 2000|journal=Australian Meteorological Magazine (Australian Meteorological and Oceanographic Journal)|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110605113928/http://www.bom.gov.au/amm/docs/2000/chappel.pdf|archivedate=June 5, 2011|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="97-98 BT"/> By 0000&nbsp;UTC on January 9, Susan had completely absorbed [[Cyclone Ron]], before the final advisories on the combined system, were released later that day as it lost its tropical characteristics and became extratropical.<ref name="97-98 ATCR"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Tropical Cyclone 11P (Susan) Warning 13 January 9, 1998 0300z|date=January 9, 1998|archivedate=January 1, 2012|deadurl=no|accessdate=July 18, 2011|author=Naval Pacific Meteorological and Oceanographic Center|url=http://www.nrlmry.navy.mil/atcf_web/docs/warnings/1998/sh111998.98010906.wrn|publisher=United States Navy, United States Air Force|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/64TjgNn1W}}</ref> The remnants of the combined system were then monitored for another day, until they were last noted during January 10, bringing an unseasonable cold snap to New Zealand.<ref name="Wellington BT"/><ref>{{cite news|date=January 10, 1998|location=New Zealand|newspaper=The Southland Times|publisher=The Southland Times Co. Ltd.|page=1|title=Blame Cyclone Susan for cold snap}}{{subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref>

===Intensity===
According to RSMC Nadi, Susan had peak 10-minute sustained windspeeds of 230&nbsp;km/h (145&nbsp;mph) which made it a category five severe tropical cyclone on the [[Tropical cyclone scales#Australia and Fiji|Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]].<ref name="97-98 BT"/><ref>{{cite news|agency=Australian Associated Press|title=Cyclone Katrina no longer a threat to Australian coast|date=January 6, 1998}}{{Subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> RSMC Nadi also estimated that Susan had an estimated minimum pressure of 900&nbsp;hPa (26.58&nbsp;inHg), which made it one of the two most intense tropical cyclones on record in the Southern Pacific.<ref name="97-98 BT"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Fiji group on alert as cyclone moves closer|date=January 7, 1998|agency=Australian Associated Press}} {{Subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> This record was subsequently broken in 2002, when [[Cyclone Zoe|Severe Tropical Cyclone Zoe]] had an estimated minimum pressure of 890&nbsp;hPa (26.28&nbsp;inHg) and became the most intense tropical cyclone on record in the southern Pacific and Australian basins.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Hall, Jonty C|author2=Callaghan, Jeff|date=April 12, 2003|title=Tropical Cyclone Zoe&nbsp;<U+2014> the most intense Tropical Cyclone observed in the Australia/South Pacific region?|publisher=Australian Meteorological and Oceanographic Society|volume=16|issue=April 2003|pages=31<U+2013>36|url=http://www.amos.org.au/documents/item/52|accessdate=January 12, 2012|journal=Bulletin of the Australian Meteorological and Oceanographic Society}}</ref>

==Preparations and impact==
Cyclone Susan caused 1 death and at least {{ntsp|100000||US$}} worth of damage, when it affected Vanuatu and Fiji during January 1998.<ref name="Susan Prem report"/> Due to the impact of this storm, the name Susan was [[List of retired South Pacific tropical cyclone names#Tropical cyclone names retired in the 1990s|retired]] from the [[lists of tropical cyclone names]].<ref name="WMO TCOP">{{cite report|author=RA V Tropical Cyclone Committee|publisher=World Meteorological Organization|url=http://www.wmo.int/pages/prog/www/tcp/documents/TCP24_RAVOpPlan_2012.pdf|type=Tropical Cyclone Operational Plan for the South-East Indian Ocean and the Southern Pacific Ocean 2012|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=December 14, 2012|pages=2B-1 - 2B-4 (23 - 26)|format=PDF|title=List of Tropical Cyclone Names withdrawn from use due to a Cyclone's Negative Impact on one or more countries|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6FYvknJAH|archivedate=April 1, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref>

===Vanuatu===
On January 5, the Vanuatu National Disaster Management Council issued various tropical cyclone alerts for various islands to warn residents about the approaching cyclone, which included a red alert for the [[Maewo]], [[Pentecost Island|Pentecost]] and [[Aoba Island|Ambae]] islands.<ref name="red">{{cite news|title=Cyclone Susan triggers red alert in Vanautu|date=January 5, 1998|work=Agence France Presse}}{{Subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref><ref name="Blows">{{cite news|title=Cyclone Susan blows towards Fiji|date=January 7, 1998|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1998/Cyclone-Susan-Blows-Toward-Fiji/id-fcaf65cbd184abe6c5bd1920ba16e7cf|work=The Associated Press|author=Keith-Reid, Robert|accessdate=January 10, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69PIrUsxb|archivedate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> Because of the upcoming cyclone Vanuatu's national radio extended its programming to run throughout the night of January 5<U+2013>6, while Vanuatu's domestic airline [[Vanair]] closed its airfields in the northern islands and cancelled all of its flights except for several direct flights between [[Santo Island]] and [[Port Vila]] the capital city of Vanuatu.<ref name="red"/> All ships and small boats were advised to seek refuge due to the high seas and swells that were expected from Susan.<ref name="red"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Cyclone Susan threatens Vanuatu|date=January 4, 1998|work=Agence France Presse}}{{Subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref> However during the afternoon of January 7, Susan recurved towards the southeast and the Fijian islands "just in time to spare Vanuatu, a direct hit.<ref name="97-98 ATCR"/> Despite being spared a direct hit, heavy rain and gale force winds were reported to have caused minor damage to several [[Vanuatuan Islands]], including on [[Aoba Island|Ambrym Island]], where a woman died after being hit by a falling coconut tree, while gathering supplies to secure her house with.<ref name="1997-98 BoM"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Cyclone Susan leaves Vanautu, Katrina approaches|date=January 6, 1998|work=Agence French Press}}{{Subscription required|via=Lexis Nexis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19980111&id=t4lGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=U-kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4852,2312229|title=Earthweek: a diary of the planet for the week ending January 9, 1998|last=Newman|first=Steve|date=January 9, 1998|work=The Sunday Gazette|pages=F5|accessdate=January 13, 2012}}</ref> After the alerts were cancelled on January 7, by the National Disaster Management Council, most shops and government buildings on Efate island kept their shutters up because [[Cyclone Katrina]] was predicted to affect the archipelago within a few days.<ref name="Blows"/>

===Fiji===
Late on January 6, RSMC Nadi issued a [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches#Australia and the South Pacific|tropical cyclone alert]] for Fiji, while Susan was located about {{convert|600|km|mi|disp=5|abbr=on}} to the west of [[Nadi, Fiji]].<ref name="Susan Prem report"/> The alert stated that Susan, was expected to pass as close as {{convert|300|km|mi|disp=5|abbr=on}} to the southwest of [[Viti Levu]] during the next day.<ref name="Susan Prem report"/> It also warned that there was a chance that the cyclone would curve more towards the east-southeast and bring gale force or stronger winds over Fiji.<ref name="Susan Prem report"/> Early the next day as squally strong north to north-easterly winds were starting to affect Fiji, RSMC Nadi upgraded the alert to a [[Tropical cyclone warnings and watches#Australia and the South Pacific|gale warning]] for [[Vatulele]], [[Kadavu Island|Kadavu]], western and south-western [[Viti Levu]] and the [[Yasawa]] and [[Mamanuca]] island groups.<ref name="Susan Prem report"/>

On January 7 and 8, Susan passed close enough to Fiji, to cause some minor coastal damage to several southern and western Fijian islands, including on the main island of Viti Levu.<ref name="1997-98 BoM"/> The cyclone also brought with it some beneficial rainfall which helped to ease the drought conditions that were present in Fiji.<ref name="Blows"/> However, gale force winds, high seas, a heavy swell and storm surge inundated Bequ Island and a village on Kadavu Island, while partly destroying beach-fronts, roads, jetties and bridges within the archipelago.<ref name="1997-98 BoM"/> Within [[Lautoka]] several shops, power lines, a bus station and the roof of a shopping complex were damaged after what was believed to be either a [[tornado]] or tornadic winds developed in one of Susan's [[rainbands]] as it crossed the shoreline.<ref name="97-98 ATCR"/><ref name="Susan Prem report"/><ref name="Lautoka">{{cite web|url=http://archives.pireport.org/archive/1998/january/01-08-up.html|title=Cyclone Susan hits Lautoka, Fiji|author=Pacific Islands Report|date=January 8, 1998|accessdate=July 26, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/60S6qeNiX|archivedate=July 26, 2011|publisher=Pacific Islands Development Program/Center for Pacific Islands Studies}}</ref> Firemen and linesmen from the [[Fiji Electricity Authority]] were called in to assist police to clear downed power wires.<ref name="Lautoka"/>

